  "prompt": "What is the appropriate way to use Ms., Mrs., and Miss?",
  "response": "The appropriate use of Ms., Mrs., and Miss depends on the individual's preference and marital status. Here\u2019s a brief overview of each title:\n\n1. **Ms.**: This title is used for women regardless of their marital status. It is a neutral option that does not indicate whether a woman is married or single. It is the preferred title when you are unsure of a woman\u2019s marital status or when addressing professional women.\n\n2. **Mrs.**: This title is traditionally used for women who are married. It typically precedes the woman's husband's last name or her own if she retained it after marriage (e.g., Mrs. Smith or Mrs. Jane Smith). It indicates marital status and is often used in more formal settings.\n\n3. **Miss**: This title is used for unmarried women and girls. It typically refers to younger women or women who have not changed their surname after marriage (e.g., Miss Johnson). \n\nWhen in doubt, using \"Ms.\" is usually a safe and respectful choice, as it allows for the acknowledgment of a woman's identity without assumptions about her marital status. Always consider individual preferences as some women may have a strong preference for one title over another.",
